column34: Before I gained my doctorate, I preferred 'Miss' on the grounds that I identify as a woman for sex, and that still affects how most people treat me, and I don't see why I should be ashamed of not being married or give up the title I hate at birth. That said, getting a gender-neutral title was a driving force for getting my doctorate, and now that I have it I feel conflicted about it. Few people actually respect or are willing to give me the title and I'm conscious that most people do not have the opportunity to earn or even opt into having a gender-neutral title. Unless I know someone has a professional or academic title, I prefer not to use one at all.

column88: I would have liked to have said, in answer to the other-things-being-equal which pronoun do I prefer question: 'Other, but I don't know what'. I couldn't because I was then required to specify. Overall, I would prefer a single set of pronouns that could be used by anyone, but find the commonly offered ones do not fit well for me. 'They' still feels plural (although I am happy to use as singular for others) but others (Xie/Hir) are too difficult to say and don't fit easily into my speech. I am more than happy to use them for those who do prefer them, but they don't feel right for me. In the absence of all else, I am fine with she/her/hers, but I wish gender just didn't come up for pronouns.

column34:
I have ***really, really, really strong feelings about this***.

What is a title?

A title is a vestige of the linguistic convention used earlier to indicate, essentially, the property-owning or owned by whom status of a human subject.

E.g.: Mr. Jones is 'Mister' because he owns, and therefore 'runs', and therefore is 'master' of the dwelling/household/the inhabitants thereof that he has title to. John Fishwell, from round the corner/down the lane, is not 'entitled' to the title of Mr. Fishwell, because he does not own anything he could be called master of. This was the matter of fact of title-usage until some point within the last ~100 years. Convention has changed, yet has preserved its linguistic stranglehold at the same time: Everyone is allowed a title; therefore everyone *must* have a title.

I want no title.

Grant to all, equally, their preferred title.

But grant to me the right to be known, recognised and recorded, simply, as myself

column88:
This is an awesome census and I'm glad to have helped take part in it.  

To clarify exactly how my gender identity works/how I currently conceptualize it: i fluctuate between masculine-ish, feminine-ish, both-at-once, a genderqueer feeling that I imagine on a Z-axis if masculinity was an X-axis and femininity a Y-axis (there's really not a better way to explain this, I'm sorry)  and occasionally feeling that the concept of gender is totaly alien to me.  There's both short-term and long-term fluctuation-I seem to go months at at time where my default is more masculine, and then flip to feeling more feminine for several months, with short-term fluctuations happening all the time.

Some things I think it'd be interesting to ask about/gather data on:

-how many of your friends turned out to also be nonbinary, if you met them while they were still living as a binary gender?
-did you try to do gender-transgressing things as a child? around puberty?  
-what imagery/symbols do you use to explain your gender identity? (I use rainbows, unicorns, and iridescence a lot)

column88: As much as I dislike the idea of telling other people that their self-determined gendered pronouns are incorrect, I am very uncomfortable with the idea of 'fae' as a pronoun. It feels appropriative. Even if it isn't appropriative for everyone using it, people for whom it would be appropriative might be encouraged to adopt it just by seeing it listed as an option without context. I am less uncomfortable with but still concerned by the suggestion of 'it' as a pronoun -- while I am aware that some people who identify as agender (or a similar descriptor) choose to be referred to as 'it', 'it' unfortunately has a long history of being used as an insult against gender nonconforming people, and continues to be used that way... which is again context missing from the list presented.

column88: I consider it important to distinguish between sex and gender and am a trans-medicalist of sorts. I have more sex characteristics in common with female than male, therefore consider  myself to be essentially female, and transsex.  However  I also think gender is constructed and not necessarily tied with sex, which itself is a conflation of multiple characteristics.  As I don't gender behaviour, thought processes, dress, preferences, mannerisms and other expressive qualities, I therefore consider myself non-binary also.  Most folk would label me 'woman' and I am happy with that, but specifically I consider myself transsex, female and non-binary.

column88: I checked a lot of boxes because I'm still sorting out how I want to identify; this is mainly because I spent most of my life not experience dysphoria for being a girl. There just wasn't much pressure to be femme or conform to gender norms I wasn't comfortable with. People didn't call attention to my gender much at all. But as an adult, I'm learning more about this new-to-me set of gendered expectations and alignments. I don't feel any different, but I no longer fit. I'm not even sure I can put my finger on what's changed, I just know that even in the most neutral or positive contexts, I do not feel comfortable being called or seen as a "woman." Maybe these words and their conceptions need to change to be more encompassing (well this is definitely true), but for me gender is a cultural/societal construct outside of me and not a felt, internal thing - I feel like an imposter no matter gendered words I use, especially when gender (and therefore those words) can mean something deeply personal to other folk. Maybe I'm overthinking it. Or maybe thinking about it a lot is exactly what makes this important to me.

column88: While it is a very nice effort, the methodological problems of autoselection, mean that your survey will only target those individuals with certain sociodemographic characteristics, such as certain economic bavkground and access to technology. Also, those willing to answer, will probably be those most invested on the subject, i.e. those most vocal about it. These type of people usually less moderate than the average person. This of course, doesn't render the survey useless, but you sbould be aware of these problems, in order to account for any bias that may come from them.

PLURAL "they"

Recognition that "they" is a historically valid and grammatically correct singular is deeply important. but for some of us, the possibility of multiplicity within "they" is important - those with multiple gender identities, genderfluid/flux/fuck. also, for those who are dissociative in nature (multiple personalities with distinct gender identities coexisting within the same body).

column88:
RE: The pronoun question, in my native language (german) the only pronoun choices are she(sie)/he(er)/it(es), plural and formal you are also both she(sie), despite not being out about my gender to anyone i generally avoid gendering myself with pronouns(easy) or mix it up with the nouns (not so easy, because every fucking word in german has a fucking gender...because reasons...). I did in fact use it(es) for a while when I was 15/16 (I am 25 now), but I did not know that people could be trans and/or nonbinary at the time and I in general avoid this set of pronouns for people nowadays, because a) It sounds sort of dehumanizing/objectifying and b) I used it because I was extremely alienated with myself because all I knew was 1. I was somehow not like other people, 2. Many of my peers intensly disliked me for no obvious reason that I could easily fixed so 3. I must be some type of weird "thing" so clearly an "it"
Good luck with your census! :)

column88: I suffered gender dysphoria from my late teens, during a period that (not coincidentally) came after leaving an all-girls' school. I felt much more comfortable doing "men's" activities and much more interested in the men's conversations, but was made to feel like I didn't belong there. I felt like I was being squeezed into a mold I was supposed to fit but didn't. I became suicidal and self-harmed because I was so convinced I was "wrong", and at that time I thought I was the only person in the world to feel that way. Eventually I decided I didn't want to kill myself as it would cause so much pain to my family and friends, so I would have to find a way to live with myself. Slowly I began questioning why I wasn't accepted the way I was, and why a girl/woman was "supposed" to be a certain way. Although I had never liked my developing female body, it was only when I moved into a two-sex environment, in which I was seen as a "woman" and not just a "person", that I became deeply unhappy. I became gender-critical, although it was many years before I heard the term. I am female, in that I have a body that produces eggs and not sperm. I may not like the fact that my body is female, but I have accepted it, just as I later had to accept a disabled body and will eventually have to accept an elderly body. I know that some people with gender dysphoria choose to transition, but that was not the choice I made. (I didn't even know it was possible back then.) Living in a small female body has made me vulnerable, and I am concerned about larger stronger male-bodied people in certain spaces because of that fact, which sometimes brings me into disagreement with transactivists even though we share the same background of gender dysphoria.  I am female and look like it, but I absolutely detest anybody calling me "cis" and find it offensive. I did not choose a "gender identity". Rather, I reluctantly accepted the body I have, and I believe that due to different treatment throughout life I am not the person I would have been had I been born male.
